<sect2 id="gimp-filter-gaussian-blur-selective">
  <title>Selective Gaussian Blur</title>

  <indexterm>
    <primary>Filters</primary>
    <secondary>Blur</secondary>
    <tertiary>Selective Gaussian</tertiary>
  </indexterm>
  <indexterm>
    <primary>Selective Gaussian Blur</primary>
  </indexterm>

  <sect3>
    <title>Overview</title>
    <figure>
      <title>The Selective Gaussian Blur filter</title>
      <mediaobject>
        <imageobject>
          <imagedata fileref="images/filters/examples/taj_orig.jpg"
            format="JPG"/>
        </imageobject>
        <caption>
          <para>Original</para>
        </caption>
      </mediaobject>
      <mediaobject>
        <imageobject>
          <imagedata fileref="images/filters/examples/blur-taj-selective.jpg"
            format="JPG"/>
        </imageobject>
        <caption>
          <para>Blur applied</para>
        </caption>
      </mediaobject>
    </figure>
    <para>
      Contrary to the other blur plug-ins, the Selective Gaussian Blur plug-in
      doesn't act on all pixels: blur is applied only if the difference
      between its value and the value of the surrounding pixels is less than a
      defined Delta value. So, contrasts are preserved because difference is
      high on contrast limits. It is used to blur a background so that the
      foreground subject will stand out better. This add a sense of depth to
      the image with only a single operation.
    </para>
  </sect3>

  <sect3>
    <title>Activate the filter</title>
    <para>
      You can find this filter in the image menu under
      <menuchoice>
        <guimenu>Filters</guimenu>
        <guisubmenu>Blur</guisubmenu>
        <guimenuitem>Selective Gaussian Blurâ€¦</guimenuitem>
      </menuchoice>
    </para>
  </sect3>

  <sect3>
    <title>Options</title>
    <figure>
      <title>
        <quote>Selective Gaussian</quote> filter parameters settings
      </title>
      <mediaobject>
        <imageobject>
          <imagedata format="PNG"
            fileref="images/filters/blur/gaussian-selective-options.png"/>
        </imageobject>
      </mediaobject>
    </figure>
    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><guilabel>Presets</guilabel>, <guilabel>Preview</guilabel>, 
          <guilabel>Split view</guilabel></term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            These options are common to GEGL-based filters. Please refer to 
            <xref linkend="gimp-filters-common"/>.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><guilabel>Aux. input</guilabel></term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            If there is another image on screen, you can select it as 
            auxiliary input.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><guilabel>Blur radius</guilabel></term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            Here you can set the blur intensity, in pixels.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><guilabel>Max. delta</guilabel></term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            Here you can set the maximum difference (0-255) between the
            pixel value and the surrounding pixel values. Above this Delta,
            blur will not be applied to that pixel.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
  </sect3>
</sect2>
